<section xml:id="section-completing-the-square-and-vertex-form">

    <title>Completing the Square and Vertex Form</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>In this section, we will learn the skill of completing the square. We will use this skill to solve quadratic equations and graph quadratic functions.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="3LB4fUyyCL8" />
        </figure>DrHgyPFR_0s
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Quadratic Equations by Completing the Square</title>

        <p>We can solve the following quadratic equation by the square root property:<md>
            <mrow>(x+5)^2\amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt{(x+5)^2}\amp=\pm\sqrt{4}</mrow>
            <mrow>x+5\amp=\pm2</mrow>
            <mrow>x+5=2\amp\text{ or }x+5=-2</mrow>
            <mrow>x=-3\amp\text{ or }x=-7</mrow>
        </md>Now, let's change the original equation this way:<md>
            <mrow>(x+5)^2\amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+5x+25\amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+5x\amp=-21</mrow>
        </md>This implies we can solve the equation <m>x^2+10x=-21</m> by the square root property. The challenge is how to convert <m>x^2+10x=-21</m> to <m>(x+5)^2=4</m>. The skill of completing the square can help us do this conversion.</p>

        <p>We have learned the perfect square formula:<me>(x+a)^2=x^2+2ax+a^2</me>Let's use this formula for some numbers, and write the equations backward:<md>
            <mrow>x^2+2x+1\amp=(x+1)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+4x+4\amp=(x+2)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+6x+9\amp=(x+3)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+8x+16\amp=(x+4)^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\ldots</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+2ax+a^2\amp=(x+a)^2</mrow>
        </md>Say we start with <m>x^2+10x</m> and try to convert it to a perfect square in the form of <m>(x+a)^2</m>. This is a two-step process.</p>

        <p>Step One: Determine the value of <m>a</m> in <m>x^2+10x+\ldots=(x+a)^2</m>. By the formula <m>x^2+2ax+a^2=(x+a)^2</m>, <m>a</m>'s value is half of <m>10</m>, so we have:<me>x^2+10x+\ldots=(x+5)^2</me></p>

        <p>Step Two: Determine the missing part in <m>x^2+10x+\ldots=(x+5)^2</m>. By the formula <m>x^2+2ax+a^2=(x+a)^2</m>, the missing part is <m>a^2</m>, or <m>5^2=25</m> for <m>(x+5)^2</m>. Now we can complete the square for <m>x^2+10x</m>:<me>x^2+10x+25=(x+5)^2</me></p>

        <p>Let's go back to solving <m>x^2+10x=-21</m>. By <m>x^2+10x+25=(x+5)^2</m>, we will add <m>25</m> on both sides of the equation, and we have:<md>
            <mrow>x^2+10x\amp=-21</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+10x\addright{25}\amp=-21\addright{25}</mrow>
            <mrow>(x+5)^2\amp=4</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt{(x+5)^2}\amp=\pm\sqrt{4}</mrow>
            <mrow>x+5\amp=\pm2</mrow>
            <mrow>x+5=2\amp\text{ or }x+5=-2</mrow>
            <mrow>x=-3\amp\text{ or }x=-7</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>So far, we only covered one of the perfect square formulas. Sometimes we need to use the other one, <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, like in the next example.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-solving-quadratic-equation-by-completing-the-sqaure-y2-20y-21">
            <statement>
                <p>Use the skill of completing the square to solve for <m>y</m> in <m>y^2-20y-21=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To use the skill of completing the square, we will first move the constant term to the right side of the equal sign:<md>
                    <mrow>y^2-20y-21\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y^2-20y\amp=21</mrow>
                </md>Next, we will complete the square.</p>
                <p>Step One: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>y^2-20y+\ldots=(y-10)^2</m>.</p>
                <p>Step Two: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>y^2-20y+100=(y-10)^2</m>.</p>
                <p>To solve the equation, we need to add <m>100</m> on both sides of the equation:<md>
                    <mrow>y^2-20y\amp=21</mrow>
                    <mrow>y^2-20y\addright{100}\amp=21\addright{100}</mrow>
                    <mrow>(y-10)^2\amp=121</mrow>
                    <mrow>\sqrt{(y-10)^2}\amp=\pm\sqrt{121}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y-10\amp=\pm11</mrow>
                    <mrow>y-10=11\amp\text{ or }y-10=-11</mrow>
                    <mrow>y=21\amp\text{ or }y=-1</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Sometimes we have to deal with fractions when we complete the square, like in the next example.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Use the skill of completing the square to solve for <m>z</m> in <m>z^2-3z-10=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>we will first move the constant term to the right side of the equal sign:<md>
                    <mrow>z^2-3z-10\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>z^2-3z\amp=10</mrow>
                </md>Next, we will complete the square.</p>
                <p>Step One: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>z^2-3y+\ldots=(z-\frac{3}{2})^2</m>.</p>
                <p>Step Two: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>z^2-3z+\frac{9}{4}=(z-\frac{3}{2})^2</m>.</p>
                <p>To solve the equation, we need to add <m>\frac{9}{4}</m> on both sides of the equation:<md>
                    <mrow>z^2-3z\amp=10</mrow>
                    <mrow>z^2-3z\addright{\frac{9}{4}}\amp=10\addright{\frac{9}{4}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>(z-\frac{3}{2})^2\amp=\frac{40}{4}+\frac{9}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>(z-\frac{3}{2})^2\amp=\frac{49}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\sqrt{(z-\frac{3}{2})^2}\amp=\pm\sqrt{\frac{49}{4}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>z-\frac{3}{2}\amp=\pm\frac{7}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>z-\frac{3}{2}=\frac{7}{2}\amp\text{ or }z-\frac{3}{2}=-\frac{7}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>z=\frac{7}{2}+\frac{3}{2}\amp\text{ or }z=-\frac{7}{2}+\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>z=5\amp\text{ or }z=-2</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>When there is a coefficient for <m>x^2</m>, like <m>2x^2+6x</m>, we need to remove it before completing the square. Let's look at the next example.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-solving-quadratic-equation-by-completing-the-square-with-leading-coefficient">
            <statement>
                <p>Use the skill of completing the square to solve for <m>r</m> in <m>2r^2+2r=1</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Because there is a leading coefficient, we will remove it by multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>2r^2+2r\amp=1</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{2}}(2r^2+2r)\amp=\multiplyleft{\frac{1}{2}}1</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{1}{2}\cdot2r^2+\frac{1}{2}\cdot2r\amp=\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r^2+r\amp=\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                </md>Next, we will complete the square.</p>
                <p>Step One: By <m>x^2+2ax+a^2=(x+a)^2</m>, we have <m>r^2+r+\ldots=(r+\frac{1}{2})^2</m>.</p>
                <p>Step Two: By <m>x^2+2ax+a^2=(x+a)^2</m>, we have <m>r^2+r+\frac{1}{4}=(r+\frac{1}{2})^2</m>.</p>
                <p>To solve the equation, we need to add <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> on both sides of the equation:<md>
                    <mrow>r^2+r\amp=\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r^2+r\addright{\frac{1}{4}}\amp=\frac{1}{2}\addright{\frac{1}{4}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>(r+\frac{1}{2})^2\amp=\frac{2}{4}+\frac{1}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>(r+\frac{1}{2})^2\amp=\frac{3}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\sqrt{(r+\frac{1}{2})^2}\amp=\pm\sqrt{\frac{3}{4}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r+\frac{1}{2}\amp=\pm\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r+\frac{1}{2}=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\amp\text{ or }r+\frac{1}{2}=-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}-\frac{1}{2}\amp\text{ or }r=-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}-\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r=\frac{\sqrt{3}-1}{2}\amp\text{ or }r=\frac{-\sqrt{3}-1}{2}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

