    <subsection>
        <title>Quadratic Function in Vertex Form</title>

        <p>We have learned the standard form of quadratic functions:<me>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</me>In this subsection, we will learn the vertex form:<me>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</me></p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="02h9yhc7ruc" />
            <video youtube="L8-7QepRSi8" />
        </figure>

        <p>A quadratic function's vertex represents the function's maximum or minimum value, which is often of interest. The next example reviews how to locate the vertex.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>In <xref ref="example-multiplying-binomials-artist-income">Example</xref>, we learned artist Michael's annual income from paintings can be modeled by <m>f(x)=-10x^2+150x+1000</m>, where <m>x</m> is the number of times he will raise the price per painting by <dollar/><m>2.00</m>. To maximumize his income, how should Michael set his price per painting?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The function is quadratic. Identify that <m>a=-10, b=150</m> and <m>c=1000</m>.</p>

                <p>Since the leading coefficient is negative, its graph is an upside down parabola. The maximum income is represented by the parabola's vertex.</p>

                <p>The first step to find the vertex is to find the parabola's axis, which is calculated by the formula:<md>
                    <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{b}{2a}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-\frac{150}{2(-10)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=7.5</mrow>
                </md>Since a parabola's vertex is on its axis, the vertex is at <m>(7.5,y)</m>. To find the missing <m>y</m> value, we substitute <m>x=7.5</m> into <m>f(x)</m>, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=-10x^2+150x+1000</mrow>
                    <mrow>f(7.5)\amp=-10(7.5)^2+150(7.5)+1000</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=1562.5</mrow>
                </md>The parabola's vertex is at <m>(7.5,1562.5)</m>. This implies Michael should raise the price per painting <m>7.5</m> times, or by <m>7.5\cdot2=15</m> dollars. This would make the price per painting <m>10+15=25</m> dollars,  and his annual income from paintings would become <dollar/><m>1562.50</m> by this math model.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>It would be great if we can convert the function <m>f(x)=-10x^2+150x+1000</m> to a form such that we can easily tell the parabola's vertex. We will use the skill of completing the square to convert the function from standard form to vertex form.</p>

        <p>There is a leading coefficient, <m>-10</m>. When we solve the equation in <xref ref="example-solving-quadratic-equation-by-completing-the-square-with-leading-coefficient">Example</xref>, we removed the leading coefficient. Let's try to use the same skill:<md>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp=-10x^2+150x+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{10}}f(x)\amp=\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{10}}(-10x^2+150x+1000)</mrow>
            <mrow>-\frac{1}{10}f(x)\amp=x^2-15x-100</mrow>
        </md>When we write the function <m>f(x)</m>, we cannot write the left side as <m>-\frac{1}{10}f(x)</m>. This skill doesn't help us here, but it worked for the equation in <xref ref="example-solving-quadratic-equation-by-completing-the-square-with-leading-coefficient">Example</xref> because the other side of the equation is <m>0</m>.</p>

        <p>To complete the square for <m>f(x)=-10x^2+150x+1000</m>, we cannot remove <m>-10</m>; instead, we have to factor it out:<md>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp=-10x^2+150x+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10(x^2-15x)+1000</mrow>
        </md>Next, we will complete the square for <m>x^2-15x</m>:</p>
        <p>Step One: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>x^2-15x+\ldots=(x-7.5)^2</m>.</p>
        <p>Step Two: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>x^2-15x+56.25=(x-7.5)^2</m>.</p>

        <p>Now we can continue the conversion:<md>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp=-10x^2+150x+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10(x^2-15x)+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10(x^2-15x+56.25-56.25)+1000</mrow>
        </md>This is again different from what we did earlier. When we solved the equation in <xref ref="example-solving-quadratic-equation-by-completing-the-sqaure-y2-20y-21">Example</xref>, we added a number on both sides of the equation. Here, we cannot do that since <m>x^2-15x</m> is inside a pair of parenthesis. We have to add <m>56.25</m> because we need it to complete the square, but we must immediately subtract it to keep the function's value unchanged. In other words, we cannot "throw in" a number into a function simply because we need it.</p>

        <p>The full process of completing the square for <m>f(x)</m> is:<md>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp=-10x^2+150x+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10(x^2-15x)+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10(x^2-15x+56.25-56.25)+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10[(x-7.5)^2-56.25]+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10(x-7.5)^2+562.5+1000</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-10(x-7.5)^2+1562.5</mrow>
        </md>If we substitute <m>x=7.5</m> into <m>f(x)=-10(x-7.5)^2+1562.5</m>, we will have:<md>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp=-10(x-7.5)^2+1562.5</mrow>
            <mrow>f(7.5)\amp=-10(7.5-7.5)^2+1562.5</mrow>
            <mrow>f(7.5)\amp=-10(0)+1562.5</mrow>
            <mrow>f(7.5)\amp=1562.5</mrow>
        </md>This is why it's easy to tell the vertex of <m>f(x)=-10(x-7.5)^2+1562.5</m> is <m>(7.5,1562.5)</m>. We call this form the <term>vertex form</term> of a quadratic function. In general, it looks like<me>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</me>and the parabola's vertex is at <m>(h,k)</m>.</p>

        <p>You might wonder why <m>(7.5,1562.5)</m> must be the parabola's vertex, instead of a different point on the parabola. This can be explained by the function's range. We know the square of a number must be positive or zero, so we have:<md>
            <mrow>(x-7.5)^2\amp\ge0</mrow>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{-10}(x-7.5)^2\amp\le\multiplyleft{-10}0</mrow>
            <mrow>-10(x-7.5)^2\amp\le0</mrow>
            <mrow>-10(x-7.5)^2\addright{1562.5}\amp\le0\addright{1562.5}</mrow>
            <mrow>-10(x-7.5)^2+1562.5\amp\le1562.5</mrow>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp\le1562.5</mrow>
        </md>The result implies the maximum value of <m>f(x)</m> is <m>1562.5</m>, making <m>(7.5,1562.5)</m> the parabola's vertex.</p>

        <p>Let's look at a few examples on the vertex form.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the vertex of the parabola <m>p(x)=-(x+2)^2+3</m>, and then sketch the graph.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>For <m>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</m>, the vertex is <m>(h,k)</m>.</p>
                <p>For <m>p(x)=-(x+2)^2+3</m>, the vertex is <m>(-2,3)</m>. We can quickly verify this by substituting <m>x=-2</m> into <m>p(x)</m>, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>p(-2)\amp=-(-2+2)^2+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=0+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=3</mrow>
                </md>If we made a mistake and said the vertex is <m>(2,3)</m>, we can easily detect it once we substitute <m>x=2</m> into <m>p(x)</m>, as we would not get <m>p(2)=3</m>.</p>

                <p>Once we find the vertex, we need at least one more point to sketch the parabola. An easy point to find is its <m>y</m>-intercept. We will substitute <m>x=0</m> into the function, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>p(x)\amp=-(x+2)^2+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>p(0)\amp=-(0+2)^2+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-4+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-1</mrow>
                </md>The parabola's <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-1)</m>. Now we can sketch its graph:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>p(x)=-(x+2)^2+3</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=5,xmin=-5,xmax=2,
                                        ytick={-9,-7,...,3},
                                        minor ytick={-9,-7,...,3},
                                        xtick={-4,-3,...,-1},
                                        minor xtick={-4,-3,...,1},
                                        xlabel={x},ylabel={y}]
                                \addplot [<->, red, domain=-5:1.606] {-(x+2)^2+3};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(-2,3)} node[above, red] {$(-2,3)$};
                                \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(0,-1)} node[right, red] {$(0,-1)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Write the quadratic function's vertex-form equation based on the given graph.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of a parabola</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description></description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[ymin=-2,ymax=5,xmin=-1,xmax=6,
                                        ytick={-1,0,...,4},
                                        minor ytick={-1,0,...,4},
                                        xtick={1,2,...,5},
                                        minor xtick={1,2,...,5},
                                        xlabel={x},ylabel={y}]
                                \addplot [<->, red, domain=0.551:5.449] {(x-3)^2-1};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>According to the graph, the parabola's vertex is at <m>(3,-1)</m>. The function's formula must be <m>f(x)=a(x-3)^2-1</m>.</p>

                <p>According to the graph, the parabola passes the point <m>(2,0)</m> (we could have chosen a different point, and would get the same solution). To find <m>a</m>'s value, we substitute <m>x=2,y=0</m> into <m>f(x)=a(x-3)^2-1</m>, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>f(x)\amp=a(x-3)^2-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=a(2-3)^2-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=a(-1)^2-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=a(1)-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=a-1</mrow>
                    <mrow>1\amp=a</mrow>
                </md>The quadratic function's equation is<me>f(x)=(x-3)^2-1</me>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>The next example is complicated because fractions are involved, but the procedures are the same.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-completing-the-square-3x2-3x">
            <statement>
                <p>Convert the quadratic function <m>g(x)=-3x^2-3x-\frac{7}{4}</m> to vertex form, and then find its vertex.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>g(x)\amp=-3x^2-3x-\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-3(x^2+x)-\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                </md>Next, we will complete the square for <m>x^2+x</m>:</p>
                <p>Step One: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>x^2+x+\ldots=(x+\frac{1}{2})^2</m>.</p>
                <p>Step Two: By <m>x^2-2ax+a^2=(x-a)^2</m>, we have <m>x^2+x+\frac{1}{4}=(x+\frac{1}{2})^2</m>.</p>
                <p>The full process of completing the square for <m>g(x)</m> is:<md>
                    <mrow>g(x)\amp=-3x^2-3x-\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-3(x^2+x)-\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-3(x^2+x+\frac{1}{4}-\frac{1}{4})-\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-3[(x+\frac{1}{2})^2-\frac{1}{4}]-\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-3(x+\frac{1}{2})^2+\frac{3}{4}-\frac{7}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-3(x+\frac{1}{2})^2-1</mrow>
                </md>The parabola's vertex is <m>(-\frac{1}{2},-1)</m></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

