    <subsection>
        <title>Three Forms of Quadratic Functions</title>

        <p>A quadratic function can be written in one of three forms. We will use <m>q(x)=2x^2+4x-6</m> as an example. This function is in standard form now. Let's change it to vertex form:<md>
            <mrow>q(x)\amp=2x^2+4x-6</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2(x^2+2x)-6</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2(x^2+2x+1-1)-6</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2[(x+1)^2-1]-6</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2(x+1)^2-2-6</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2(x+1)^2-8</mrow>
        </md>There is a third form called the <term>factored form</term>, which looks like <m>f(x)=a(x+b)(x+c)</m>. Not all quadratic functions can be converted to the factored form. Let's try to factor the function <m>q(x)=2x^2+4x-6</m>:<md>
            <mrow>q(x)\amp=2x^2+4x-6</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2(x^2+2x-3)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2(x+3)(x-1)</mrow>
        </md>We can easily see this parabola's <m>x</m>-intercepts in this form: <m>(-3,0)</m> and <m>(1,0)</m>.</p>

        <p>Let's summarize a quadratic function's three forms:<ul>
            <li><p>Standard Form: <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m>. For example, <m>q(x)=2x^2+4x-6</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Vertex Form: <m>f(x)=a(x-h)^2+k</m>. For example, the quadratic function <m>q(x)=2(x+1)^2-8</m> is in its vertex form, and we can easily see the parabola's vertex: <m>(-1,8)</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>Factored Form: <m>f(x)=a(x+b)(x+c)</m>. For example, the quadratic function <m>q(x)=2(x+3)(x-1)</m> is in its factored form, and we can easily see the parabola's <m>x</m>-intercepts: <m>(-3,0)</m> and <m>(1,0)</m>.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
    </subsection>

