    <subsection>
        <title>Shifting Parabolas</title>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="DrHgyPFR_0s" />
        </figure>

        <p>Let's locate the vertices (plural form of "vertex") of <m>f(x)=x^2</m>, <m>g(x)=x^2+1</m> and <m>h(x)=x^2-2</m>, and then graph them. We will write them in the vertex form:<md>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp=(x-0)^2+0\amp\text{vertex: }(0,0)</mrow>
            <mrow>g(x)\amp=(x-0)^2+1\amp\text{vertex: }(0,1)</mrow>
            <mrow>h(x)\amp=(x-0)^2-2\amp\text{vertex: }(0,-2)</mrow>
        </md>Now let's look at their graphs:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Graph of <m>f(x), g(x)</m> and <m>h(x)</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-3,ymax=3,xmin=-3,xmax=3,
                                ytick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                xtick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                minor xtick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                xlabel={x},ylabel={y}]
                        \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(0,0)};
                        \addplot[red,domain=-1.732:1.732,<->]{x^2} node[pos=0.4,left] {$f(x)$};
                        \addplot [soliddot, color=blue] coordinates {(0,1)};
                        \addplot[blue,domain=-1.404:1.404,<->]{x^2+1} node[pos=0.4,left] {$g(x)$};
                        \addplot [soliddot, color=black] coordinates {(0,-2)};
                        \addplot[black,domain=-2.236:2.236,<->]{x^2-2} node[pos=0.4,left] {$h(x)$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Next, we will locate the vertices of <m>f(x)=x^2</m>, <m>p(x)=(x+1)^2</m> and <m>q(x)=(x-2)^2</m>, and then graph them.<md>
            <mrow>f(x)\amp=(x-0)^2+0\amp\text{vertex: }(0,0)</mrow>
            <mrow>p(x)\amp=(x+1)^2+0\amp\text{vertex: }(-1,0)</mrow>
            <mrow>q(x)\amp=(x-2)^2+0\amp\text{vertex: }(2,0)</mrow>
        </md>Now let's look at their graphs:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Graph of <m>f(x), p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m></caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <description></description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-3,ymax=3,xmin=-3,xmax=3,
                                ytick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                xtick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                minor xtick={-2,-1,...,2},
                                xlabel={x},ylabel={y}]
                        \addplot [soliddot, red] coordinates {(0,0)};
                        \addplot[red,domain=-1.732:1.732,<->]{x^2} node[pos=0.2,left] {$f(x)$};
                        \addplot [soliddot, color=blue] coordinates {(-1,0)};
                        \addplot[blue,domain=-2.732:0.732,<->]{(x+1)^2} node[pos=0.4,left] {$p(x)$};
                        \addplot [soliddot, color=black] coordinates {(2,0)};
                        \addplot[black,domain=0.268:3,<->]{(x-2)^2} node[pos=0.9,left] {$q(x)$};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>We can summarize some rules about shifting graphs:<ul>
            <li><p>To graph <m>g(x)=x^2+a</m>, where <m>a\gt0</m>, we shift the graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> up by <m>a</m> units.</p></li>
            <li><p>To graph <m>h(x)=x^2-a</m>, where <m>a\gt0</m>, we shift the graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> down by <m>a</m> units.</p></li>
            <li><p>To graph <m>p(x)=(x+a)^2</m>, where <m>a\gt0</m>, we shift the graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> to the left by <m>a</m> units.</p></li>
            <li><p>To graph <m>q(x)=(x-a)^2</m>, where <m>a\gt0</m>, we shift the graph of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> to the right by <m>a</m> units.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
    </subsection>

